data.text:
Stillman INT.

2006

David Baulcombe and Richard Jorgensen interviewed by Jan Witkowski [camera view of Baulcombe, Jorgensen, and Witkowski; ends at 0:18:01]; Bruce Stillman interviewed by Sydney Gary [camera view of Gary and Stillman; video 0:25:18-0:40:06]; Carol Greider interviewed by Alex Gann [camera view of Greider and Gann; 0:40:06- 0:43:22]

Cablevision Special Edition "A Century of Discovery"

1990-07

Cablevision Special Edition; Cold Spring Harbor Lab Airs 7-26-90; Producer Ann Balderston; Editor Bernard Galli; features history of CSHL and current research including cancer and neuroscience; features James D. Watson, Barbara McClintock, Susan Cooper, Michael Gilman, Tim Mulligan, Dan Schecter, Jan Witkowski, Mark Bloom, Steven Malloy, Dr. Michael Schuster, Cindy Larson, Thomas Doherty, Alan Fortunoff; features the construction of Beckman/ Neuroscience complex; July 14, 1990 centennial of the laboratory day; also features recorded news12 news segment with reporter Judy Martin about the CSHL Centenial: interview with Susan Cooper; history of CSHL; recreation of the 1890 boat;

40th Anniversary of DNA: James Watson

1993-03-02

James D. Watson talks about the significane of the discovery of the structure of DNA at the 40th Anniversary of DNA [colors seem off, but set to bars; unstable images]

40th Anniversary of DNA: Francis Crick

1993-03-01

Jan Witkowski introduces Francis Crick for his talk titled the "Double Helix". Includes recollections of the past; impression of what it was like when Crick and Watson discovered the structure of the double helix.

Dr. Hanna Gray and Dr. James Watson

1993-11-05

David Luke, Chairman of the Board of Trustees at CSHL, introduces Hanna H. Gray, President of the University of Chicago, talks about James D. Watson, Mary Lindsay, Vice President of the Board of Trustees unveils coffee table present to James D. Watson and Elizabeth Watson for their 25th Anniversary at CSHL [coffee table features painting of CSHL and double helix border], James D. Watson speaks about his anniversary

LIBA Lecture: Barbara McClintock

Barbara McClintock discusses about the Human Genome Project at a LIBA meeting; the genome of organisms; plant genomes vs. animal genomes; illustrations of plant genomes; germ lines; cell lines; questions and answers at end [lecture ends at 1:06:00] cuts to 1983 interview directed by Harvey P. Henning with Barbara McClintock about deciding to go into science; Cornell University; taking a genetics course in 1921; graduate course in genetics; chromosome course; PhD research; maize; maize propagation; plant breeding; linkage group; chromosomes; George Beadle; Marcus Rhodes; cytogenetics; 1951 Cold Spring Harbor Symposium presentation; 1953 paper; Nobel Prize award; colleagues; working with men; junior year of college geology course test-- forgetting her own name; 1951 Symposium reaction of peers and impact of McClintock she was amused; when the scientific world believed McClintock; McClintock shows/explains an experiment with an ear of corn (content used for "Nobel Prize 1983" see PA_027)

DNALC Dedication

1988-09-18

Bayard Clarkson opening remarks for dedication of the DNALC in Grace Auditorium; David Micklos speaks about the mystery of life: miracle of conception; self replication of living cells; organization of living cells; the genetic code; Hugh Mahoney Special Assistant to Tom Gulotta Nassau County Executive [Gulotta couldn't make it]; Toni Rettaliata Town Supervisor of Town of Huntington, NY; Director Dr. James D. Watson; Robert E. Pollack; [White levels set way too high adjusted to make it at least visible at beginning. Iris changes and content becomes too dark.]

Science and Man Barbara McClintock 1983 Nobel Laureates

1983-12-03

Swedish Ch. 1

"Science and Man: A Round table discussion with the 1983 Nobel Laureates in the Sciences" hosted by Bengt Feldreich and Jackie Klopp. Features McClintock and the other Laureates preparing for the ceremony, Copyright of TV1 Fakta Stockholm Sveriges Television A3 1983

James D. Watson "Genetically Engineered Insulin"

1988-12-1

"Genetically Engineered Insulin: Ten Year Prospective" at the Beckman Center Irvine, California; participating in this conference are some of the key players leading from elucidation of the structure of DNA to facile production and clinical use of genetically engineered substances for the benefit of mankind features Eugene Roberts, Beckman Research Institute City of Hope, Dr. Rachmiel Levine, James D. Watson; Marshall Warren Nirenberg; Har Gobind Khorana; Paul Berg; Herb Boyer; Robert C.L. Guillemin; Arthur Riggs; Robert Tjian; Keiichi Itakura; David Goeddel; Irving Johnson; John Galloway; and others. Sponsored by the National Academy of Sciences, the Arnold and Mabel Beckman Center of the National Academies of Sciences and Egineering and the Beckman Research institute of the City of Hope. Conference organizers: Arnold Beckman; Copyright of the Arnold and Mabel Beckman Center

Susan Cooper Interviews: Melba Toliver and Joel Martin

1990

Susan Gensel Cooper CSHL Archivist and Public Affairs Director discusses the centennial celebration of the Laboratory, history of the Lab, DNALC, Smithsonian Exhibit "A Search for Life", Barbara McClintock, [left sound channel very low and is producing static, the only significant audio is in the right channel] [ends at 0:04:39]; "The Joel Martin Show" interviews Susan Gensel Cooper, Director of Public Affairs at CSHL, they discuss the centennial of Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory; funding; Barbara McClintock; James D. Watson [0:04:40 - 0:31:36]

Alzheimers Lecture

1993-11-13

"Alzheimer's Disease: Research Challenges Ethical Considerations" Dr. Frederic Sherman, Chairman of Medical and Scientific Advisory Board of Nassau/Suffolk Counties Alzheimer's Association, Daniel Marshak CSHL, Dr. Kenneth Davis Chair of the Dept of Psychiatry and Professor of Psychology at the Mt. Sinai School of Medicine; Dr. Steven Ferris Professor in the Dept of Psychiatry at New York University Medical Center and Exec. Director of NYU's Aging and Dementia Research Program; John Zaccaro, President of the Academy of Medical Film [Tracking issue causing poor image stability and audio distortion throughout]

Panorama Project & BBC Watson Interview

circa 1990: Watson is interviewed about the importance of the Human Genome Project and the potential breakthroughs from it. [cuts to bars at end and static for rest of tape.] Copyright BBC?

Will Provine Leture Eugenics/ Genetics

John Inglis, Director of CSHLPress, introduces Will Provine from Cornell University to discuss the start of the Laboratory in 1892 and interest in human genetics about manipulation of the Human Genome; eugenics and genetics in the early years at Cold Spring Harbor [No microphone used, voice is very difficult to hear]

LIBA: Rich Roberts

1988-10-16

George Cutting introduces Richard J. Roberts and discusses Roberts being called to testisy as an expert witness on DNA fingerprinting in a case in Queens, NY; Richard J. Roberts presents on restriction enzymes, discovery of the enzymes, and his lab, and the use of restriction enzymes [Low audio levels at beginning due to speaker being far away with no microphone. Levels come back]

J. Larocca, Konrad Mathaei, and Morgan Browne

1988-11

"Long Island Talks Business" on News12 hosted by James Larocca; 35th anniversary of the discovery of the structure of the double helix; segment about CSHL; research taking place at CSHL; revolution in genetic engineering; plant genetics; DNA fingerprinting; cancer research; also discusses community outreach, DNALC, and research funding; Morgan Browne and Konrad Mathaei [Static period around 26:00 image regains after time]; Copyright of News12

Sidney Brenner

2002-07-18

Edited and titled interview: "CSHL Making Connections"; Jim Watson My Impressions"; Jim Watson as a Writer: The Double Helix, The Molecular Biology of the Gene"; "The DNA Discovery in Context: How To Achieve Greatness"; "CSHL: A Center for Science"; "CSHL Symposia"; "Women in Science"; "Milislav Demerec: CSHL Director"; "John Cairns and Joe Sambrook"; "Rich Roberts"; "CSHL The Future"

Al Hershey Interview

Video of historic CSHL photographs, interview with Al Hershey, he discusses his mediterranean cruise vacation from Lisbon to Athens; discusses Leo Szilard and why he was at CSHL; physicists coming to biology; bacteriophage; Watson and Crick; phage group (Delbruck, Luria, Hershey) Demerec brought in phage work (his decision); Delbruck recruited people to the field; influence spread outside phage because CSH Symposia; Lwoff; Monod; influence Francois Jacob; molecular biology; genetics

Ed Pulley Comments

Ed Pulling, Chairman of LIBA, Trustee of CSHL, discusses the origin and funding of LIBA; changes in LIBA's role with CSHL; reward of LIBA membership; past LIBA lecturers; founding of LIBA; neighborhood people involved: JP Morgan, Vanderbuilt, Louis Tiffany;

Watson Talk/Walk B-Roll, Rich Roberts

James Watson outside Carnegie Library; James Watson and Maureen Berejka (Watson's assistant) walk the lower roadway along the harbor; Richard J. Roberts uses a computer; interview with Richard J. Roberts; Richard J. Roberts' computer screen; Richard J. Roberts writes on a blackboard

Segment Master 1 of 4 Dubs

"Biological Revolution" Segment 2: Threshold of New Biological Revolution and Segment 3; Segment 4: Early History; Segment 6: Mendelian Genetics; Segment 7: Founding of LIBA; Segment 8: The Phage Group; Segment 9: Structure and Function of DNA; Segment 10: Recombinant DNA; Segment 11: Cancer Biology; Segment 12: Plant Biology and Development; Segment 13: Crossroads of Biology; Segment 14: Looking Toward the Future; includes Wally Gilbert, James D. Watson, Sydney Brenner, Alfred Hershey, Mike Wigler, Richard J. Roberts; Terri Grodzicker and others
